{"id": "2661", "revid": "285812", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2661", "title": "Ankheg Plate Mail", "text": "Ankheg Plate Mail is a type of in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate (game)&lt;/a&gt;\" (and '), ', ' (and '), and \"\".\nAcquisition.\n\"Baldur's Gate\" / \"Enhanced Edition\".\nIn the classic game, he will charge to craft the shell into armor. About ten days later the shiny new armor will be ready to collect. In the Enhanced Edition it costs but will be finished in three days, or more can be paid to have it ready in just one day. In order to obtain it, select option \"We don't want to sell it at the moment, but if we did, you'd be the first to know\" - then Taerom offers to make armor out of the shell.\nRegardless of game versions or how fast you want the armor made, Taerom will only craft one piece of Ankheg armor for your party; afterwards he will only buy Ankheg shells for .\n\"Siege of Dragonspear\".\nIn addition to being able to import the two sets from \"Baldur's Gate: Enhanced Edition\", &lt;a href=\"Onoroth\"&gt;Onoroth&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Bloodbark%20Grove\"&gt;Bloodbark Grove&lt;/a&gt; has one for sale.\n\"Baldur's Gate II\" / \"Enhanced Edition\".\nTo obtain this armor in \"Shadows of Amn\", bring a shell to &lt;a href=\"Cromwell\"&gt;Cromwell&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Dock%20District\"&gt;Athkatla Dock District&lt;/a&gt;. He will charge you to make the armor and you need to help him for a day. You can do this more than once.\nGameplay.\nIn the base game, Ankheg Plate armor is unique as it's the only plate armor made from the shell of an animal, rather than metal. That makes it highly valuable to certain characters/classes, and less so for others. (: In SoD and BG2, more lightweight, non-metallic armors become available such as &lt;a href=\"Rhino%20Beetle%20Plate\"&gt;Rhino Beetle&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dragonscale%20Armor\"&gt;Dragonscale)&lt;/a&gt;. \nDruids: In , Ankheg Plate is the best armor &lt;a href=\"Druid\"&gt;Druids&lt;/a&gt; can wear since it is non-metallic. If a Druid is in your party this armor is very valuable for the AC it provides, especially if taking the role of 'combat medic', since cure spells have to be cast at touch range. \nFighters: By raw numbers, Ankheg Plate is weaker by 2 AC vs. piercing/missile weapons, and 1 AC vs. slashing compared to &lt;a href=\"Full%20Plate%20Armor\"&gt;Full Plate Armor&lt;/a&gt;, but equal vs. crushing weapons.\nAdditionally, in the classic game you can't wear protection items such a &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20the%20Princes\"&gt;Ring of the Princes&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Protection%20%2B1\"&gt;Cloak of Protection +1&lt;/a&gt; with Ankheg Plate Mail. Full Plate Armor is a better choice if you also want protection gear for armor and saving throws bonuses.\nLow Strength value: Ankheg armor is nearly as strong as Full Plate, but as light as &lt;a href=\"Studded%20Leather%20Armor\"&gt;Studded Leather Armor&lt;/a&gt;. Its low &lt;a href=\"strength\"&gt;strength&lt;/a&gt; requirement of 8 also allows weaker companions like &lt;a href=\"Viconia%20DeVir\"&gt;Viconia&lt;/a&gt; to wear it and gain decent protection. The low weight also makes it a good back-up armor for Fighter / Mages and &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20/%20Mage\"&gt;Cleric / Mage&lt;/a&gt;s to keep in their inventory and put on once they have exhausted their arcane spells, so as to survive better in melee.\nTrivia.\nAnkheg Plate Mail is most likely based on Advanced Dungeons &amp; Dragons (2nd Edition) Field Plate since they share the same modifiers, although the Ankheg Plate has a base AC of 1 instead of 2. This discrepancy is could be explained by being personally crafted for the player by a master armorer."}
