{"id": "7724", "revid": "36786428", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7724", "title": "Ao", "text": "Ao, also known as Lord Ao or the Hidden One, is a &lt;a href=\"true%20neutral\"&gt;true neutral&lt;/a&gt; who rules over all other deities.\nUnlike other deities in the realms, Ao's powers are not bound to the number of his worshippers and he generally doesn't intermingle with mortals. His job is to keep the cosmic balance and keep all other deities in check, which comes with ultimate power over all other gods.\nDuring the &lt;a href=\"Time%20of%20Troubles\"&gt;Time of Troubles&lt;/a&gt;, he made all gods\u2014with the exception of &lt;a href=\"Helm\"&gt;Helm&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0whom he elected to guard the gates of &lt;a href=\"Heaven\"&gt;Heaven&lt;/a&gt;\u2014walk the realms as mortals as punishment for ignoring their worshippers and the theft of the &lt;a href=\"Tablets%20of%20Fate\"&gt;Tablets of Fate&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0performed by &lt;a href=\"Bane\"&gt;Bane&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Myrkul\"&gt;Myrkul&lt;/a&gt;.\nAccording to &lt;a href=\"Cyric\"&gt;Cyric&lt;/a&gt;, Ao banned deities from directly intervening in affairs of &lt;a href=\"Bhaal\"&gt;Bhaal&lt;/a&gt; progeny."}
{"id": "2212", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2212", "title": "Aoln", "text": "Aoln approaches &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party when they first take the &lt;a href=\"Coast%20Way\"&gt;Coast Way&lt;/a&gt; north towards the &lt;a href=\"Friendly%20Arm%20Inn\"&gt;Friendly Arm Inn&lt;/a&gt; area. He is an adventurer, and once had a band of adventurers like the party, but lost them all fighting an &lt;a href=\"Ogre%20Mage\"&gt;ogre mage&lt;/a&gt;.\nHe explains the perils of traveling and some of the basic &lt;a href=\"Enemies\"&gt;monsters&lt;/a&gt; one may face in the surrounding area. After answering one question he'll leave and disappear.\nDialogue.\n\"If ye don't mind, please try to keep your voices down. There be beasties about with better hearing than we.\""}
{"id": "14999", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14999", "title": "Aphril", "text": "Aphril is a female &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"conjurer\"&gt;conjurer&lt;/a&gt; and one of the inmates of &lt;a href=\"Spellhold\"&gt;Spellhold&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nAphril can be found on the &lt;a href=\"Spellhold%20Main%20Floor\"&gt;Spellhold Main Floor&lt;/a&gt; of the Asylum in Chapter 4 where she is one of several inmates held inside. She has her own assigned cell. Her ability to see through the planes drove her mad and she will tell the player about the things she sees and even show them.\nThe party may initiate further dialogue by speaking with her in the inmate cellblock area. Various interjections are scripted by certain core party companions.\nDuring the first meeting with the inmates, including Aphril, the group are protected from death with the &lt;a href=\"MINHP1.ITM\"&gt;MINHP1.ITM&lt;/a&gt;. They are essential to the plot script, and sometimes players recklessly try and kill everything everywhere. There will be plenty of blood spilling later in the quest, so no need to jump the gun.\nLater in the questline, Aphril will join with the party to defeat Irenicus in the final battle of the Asylum adventure. She will not be a controllable creature during the fight but will take spell casting action as scripted to defend herself and attack Irenicus and any hostile creatures in the battle zone. The conjurer has a well populated spellbook of memorized spells levels 1 through 7.\nLike all of the inmates, she later dies during the fight against &lt;a href=\"Irenicus\"&gt;Irenicus&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Spellhold%20Basement\"&gt;Spellhold Basement&lt;/a&gt;. This certain fate is scripted for plot purposes and can't be prevented.\nCross-references to other games:.\nMost notably she sees things from two other games, namely \"\" and \"&lt;a href=\"Neverwinter%20Nights\"&gt;Neverwinter Nights&lt;/a&gt;\".\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; revises Aphril's memorized spells and AI. The mod also randomly revises mage kit assignment on install, and she could be an Invoker or an Enchanter for example. This will allow a more robust initial pre-buffing of protective spells at the outset of hostilities, especially against Irenicus - who also has a deadlier initial attack phase. \nIn the unmodded game she is woefully unprepared to resist damaging spells of any kind. With SCS she has more staying power and can remain in the fight longer. The mod also furnishes Aphril with one or two potions for quaffing (two when fighting Irenicus).\nThe &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod will change her spells to the mod versions."}
{"id": "53565", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=53565", "title": "Apparition (Spellhold)", "text": "The Apparition creatures are several non-player actors for the Asylum plot and associated with the final tests needed to navigate the &lt;a href=\"Escaping%20the%20asylum\"&gt;Escaping the asylum&lt;/a&gt; questline.\nGameplay.\nThese apparitions, also called \"Arbiter\" in the game files are &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt; spirits of some type that still fulfill the mechanisms of evaluating inmates of the Spellhold asylum. Frankly, this isn't explained very well in the game, but it really isn't a mystery that has to be solved in order to progress through the various tests and hurdles to be freed from the asylum discharge process.\nThere is a total of fifteen different .CRE files associated with the apparition appearances in the game. Many of these will only be produced based on dialogue choices made when the party is replying to questions from the Arbiter. Different tests have separate .CRE files and dialogue trees. \nIn general, the more non-compliant and combative or uncooperative the party is with the Arbiters, the longer it will take to get through the tests presented by these arbiters. In many instances being recalcitrant or unaccepting of their orders results in additional remedial challenges and tests. However, further tests provide more gameplay, and a way to gain further experience and even some loot.\nThese creatures are not meant to be attacked or faced in combat. They are designed to be immune to this sort of hostile action for plot purposes. It may be possible to actually cast a spell or fire a missile weapon at some of these creatures, but it won't gain any advantage and is really a waste of energy. Although difficult to do, breaking the game script will result in a reload scenario, so don't purposely foul up the game cohesion."}
