{"id": "5804", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5804", "title": "Archaeological Site", "text": "The Archaeological Site, also known as the Area South of Lighthouse, is where Captain Brage, and Charleston Nib's archaeological site are found.\nArchaeology site.\nThough not technically a &lt;a href=\"Quests\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt;, as it lacks appropriate entry in &lt;a href=\"Journal\"&gt;Journal&lt;/a&gt;, the events at the archaeology site function much like one. They begin when &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party speak to &lt;a href=\"Charleston%20Nib\"&gt;Charleston Nib&lt;/a&gt;. After asking about your business there, Charleston asks you to assist him in protecting the site. You can push him into paying for your services with dialogue options 1, 1, 2, 3, 1.\nGallor's scheme.\nWhen he has gone, &lt;a href=\"Gallor\"&gt;Gallor&lt;/a&gt; will approach you and suggest an alternative use of your skills. He wants you to kill Charleston and his workmen so he can sell the artifacts from the excavation site. If you prefer his proposal, you should ensure you ask for a reward before agreeing. He will offer (dialogue options 2, 3, 3, 3). Alternatively, you can refuse Gallor outright.\nThe tomb.\nWhichever moral path you choose, you must talk to Charleston again outside the tomb for events to progress. You will be taken inside the tomb and, shortly after, the workers will go mad and attack. There is no other course but to kill them. Once they are dead, speak to Charleston again. You can raid the sarcophagus for the &lt;a href=\"Idol\"&gt;Idol&lt;/a&gt; of Kozah. If you're playing the original Baldur's Gate, you must do this \"after\" talking to Charleston or he'll take the idol from you. In the Enhanced Edition, however, he won't.\nOutcomes.\nHelp Charleston.\nIf you are helping Charleston, you can leave after the workers are dead and you have spoken with him again. Helping Charleston yields a reward of +1 &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt;, and depending on your dialogue choices. Gallor can be talked to afterwards, causing him to leave or safely killed for 120 XP and minor loot.\nHelp Gallor.\nIf you are working for Gallor, kill Charleston. This will cause a serious Reputation decrease, unless you charm him in order for diggers (or your summoned creatures) to do the dirty work. When you leave the tomb with the idol, a &lt;a href=\"Doomsayer\"&gt;Doomsayer&lt;/a&gt; will try to approach you. If you are quick enough to give idol to Gallor (you can also drop the idol on ground temporarily), you will get a reward of and -2 reputation. Otherwise, Gallor and the Doomslayer will turn hostile. Defensive spells and summoned creatures can help repel their attack. Killing the Doomsayer will also get you 4000 XP.\nHelp yourself.\nIf you have no interest in either helping Gallor or Charleston, you can take the Idol of Kozah to the &lt;a href=\"ghost%20of%20Ulcaster\"&gt;ghost of Ulcaster&lt;/a&gt; at the &lt;a href=\"Ulcaster\"&gt;Ulcaster Ruins&lt;/a&gt; along with the &lt;a href=\"Ancient%20Armor\"&gt;ancient armor&lt;/a&gt; from the &lt;a href=\"Firewine%20Ruins\"&gt;Firewine Ruins&lt;/a&gt;. This will earn you the dubious reward of the cursed sword &lt;a href=\"The%20Vampire%27s%20Revenge\"&gt;The Vampire's Revenge&lt;/a&gt;. Also note that it is possible to agree to help Gallor but not kill Charleston. In that case, if you have the idol when exiting the tomb, Gallor will turn hostile and attack.\nCaptain Brage.\nCaptain &lt;a href=\"Brage\"&gt;Brage&lt;/a&gt; is in the central-southeastern part of the map, very near to the archaeological site and a caravan of slain innocents. He is the target of the quest &lt;a href=\"The%20Tale%20of%20Captain%20Brage\"&gt;The Tale of Captain Brage&lt;/a&gt;, called 'Recovering Captain Brage' in classic &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. Brage is in possession of the &lt;a href=\"Two-handed%20Sword%2C%20Cursed%20Berserking%20%2B3\"&gt;Cursed Sword of Berserking +3&lt;/a&gt;, which caused him to murder many people, including his own family. If you answer his riddle correctly, he will surrender and give you the sword. You can also choose to kill him and take his sword. The body can be brought to &lt;a href=\"Oublek\"&gt;Oublek&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Nashkel\"&gt;Nashkel&lt;/a&gt; for a bounty.\nBa'ruk.\n&lt;a href=\"Ba%27ruk\"&gt;Ba'ruk&lt;/a&gt; is a hobgoblin wandering the area. Ba'ruk will greet the party and demand that they leave 'his' land. Whatever you say, he will attack with some &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Commando\"&gt;kobold commandos&lt;/a&gt;. Killing Ba'ruk gives you 165 XP, a &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword\"&gt;Bastard Sword&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Composite%20Long%20Bow\"&gt;Composite Long Bow&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Arrow\"&gt;Arrow&lt;/a&gt; x20, &lt;a href=\"Helmet\"&gt;Helmet&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Leather%20Armor\"&gt;Leather Armor&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"random%20treasure\"&gt;random treasure&lt;/a&gt;, as well as loot from kobold commandos, most notably the &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20of%20Fire\"&gt;Arrows of Fire&lt;/a&gt; if you can kill them quick enough (it is possible for them to instantly switch to their melee weapon if you manage to get to their spawn location before the dialogue begins).\nTransitions.\nOn the original &lt;a href=\"World%20Map\"&gt;World Map&lt;/a&gt;, these travel times are entirely believable, but on the revised map for the \"\" it appears to be quite impossible that travel to the Red Canyons area could be faster than to the Fisherman's Lake area."}
{"id": "11182", "revid": "271003", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11182", "title": "Archer", "text": "Archer is a &lt;a href=\"Ranger\"&gt;Ranger&lt;/a&gt; kit. Archers have full access to all five proficiency levels of any bow type, but can only have one proficiency point in any melee weapon. This includes weapons such as &lt;a href=\"dagger\"&gt;dagger&lt;/a&gt;s which can be used as ranged or melee weapons. Archers can have two proficiency points in other ranged weapons like &lt;a href=\"sling\"&gt;sling&lt;/a&gt;s. Unlike other &lt;a href=\"Ranger\"&gt;Ranger&lt;/a&gt;s they are limited to &lt;a href=\"Leather%20Armor\"&gt;leather&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Studded%20Leather%20Armor\"&gt;studded leather&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hide%20Armor\"&gt;hide armor&lt;/a&gt; and have no &lt;a href=\"Charm%20Animal\"&gt;Charm Animal&lt;/a&gt; ability.\nOnly &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;elves&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Half-elf\"&gt;half-elves&lt;/a&gt; can become archers. Archers have three prime requisites: &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dexterity\"&gt;Dexterity&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Wisdom\"&gt;Wisdom&lt;/a&gt;. They can dual-class with &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;s, though such combination has fewer benefits than the vanilla &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20/%20Ranger\"&gt;Cleric / Ranger&lt;/a&gt;. A Cleric/Archer is restricted to slings as a ranged weapon and thus loses some of the benefits of the Archer kit.\nIn the non-Enhanced version of \"Baldur's Gate II\", archers could not dual-class with Throne of Bhaal installed.\nIf the player character is an archer and commits a murder, for example, they will become a Fallen Ranger, which is a ranger without the special abilities - effectively a &lt;a href=\"Fighter\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt; without the benefits of grandmastery and slower levelling. Only in and at the end of &lt;a href=\"Ranger-Protector%20of%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Ranger-Protector of the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt;, they can become normal archers once more.\nCharacter abilities table.\nNotes:\nSpecial abilities of the archer.\nStealth.\nRangers can hide in shadows if they wear leather armor, studded leather armor or no armor. Every ranger starts with 15% in both move silently and hide in shadows, modified by racial and dexterity bonuses at level 1 to successfully hides in shadows. Attempting to hide in shadows during the day or while not in shadows incurs a penalty to the hide check. Melee attacks receive a +4 to-hit bonus if performed while hidden.\nRanged Bonuses.\nArchers receive a 1 point increase to hit and damage with any missile weapon for every 3 experience levels they obtain up to and including level 18. This slows down to once every 5 levels thereafter, reaching a +9 to-hit and damage at level 33. This bonus applies to all missile weapons, including thrown weapons and missile weapons from polymorphs such as the ranged attack of a &lt;a href=\"Mustard%20Jelly\"&gt;Mustard Jelly&lt;/a&gt;.\nCalled Shot.\nGains one use at level 4 and an additional use every 4 levels thereafter. All successful ranged attacks made by the Archer within the next 10 seconds acquire the following effects besides normal damage:\n\"Note: As an \"innate spell\", &lt;a href=\"Multi-class\"&gt;multi&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dual-class\"&gt;dual&lt;/a&gt;-classed characters \"cast\" Called Shot at the average of their class levels, rounded up.\"\nThere is no save against these effects and they ignore magic resistance. They are also cumulative, i. e., hitting an enemy several times while this ability is active applies its effects multiple times.\nRacial enemy.\nArchers tend to focus on a particular racial creature, having a +4 to hit attack bonus roll versus the racial enemy. Some of these are not available in original Baldur's Gate or Tales of the Sword Coast and were added when Shadows of Amn and Throne of Bhaal were released. Several low-level groups are only available in the first Baldur's Gate games. When importing a character from BG1 into BG2, you can choose a new racial enemy when you start a new game. The player chooses one of the types of creatures listed below:\n1 Not available in Baldur's Gate 1 (EE).\nPriest Spellbook.\nAt level 8, the priest spellbook unlocks for archers. They can use the following spells from that moment. The spells the archers are able to use are the same as &lt;a href=\"druid\"&gt;druid&lt;/a&gt;s. They can learn up to level 3 spells. Their number of spells is determined by their level and is not affected by Wisdom.\nRelated items.\nItem better for Archers:\n&lt;a href=\"Archer%27s%20Eyes\"&gt;Archer's Eyes&lt;/a&gt; \nAchievements.\nIncreasing the &lt;a href=\"Weapon%20Proficiency\"&gt;proficiency&lt;/a&gt; with any ranged &lt;a href=\"weapon\"&gt;weapon&lt;/a&gt; to five points, becoming a \"Grand Master\", will unlock an &lt;a href=\"achievement\"&gt;achievement&lt;/a&gt; in the \"\"."}
{"id": "16723", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=16723", "title": "Archer's Eyes", "text": "The Archer's Eyes is an &lt;a href=\"amulet\"&gt;amulet&lt;/a&gt; that augments the wearer's ranged attacks. First appearing in ', this item can be &lt;a href=\"Importing%23cite_note-5\"&gt;imported&lt;/a&gt; into the '."}
{"id": "54978", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=54978", "title": "Archer (North Forest)", "text": "Archer is a fighter class female human creature encountered during &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%206\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II Chapter 6&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"North%20Forest%20%28Shadows%20of%20Amn%29\"&gt;North Forest (Shadows of Amn)&lt;/a&gt; area.\nGameplay.\nThis archer is part of an unknown mixed group of adventurers or perhaps mercenaries encountered in about the center of the area map. The whole group is hostile to any intruders that are detected.\nThe archer will try and fire missiles unless engaged in melee range and unable to backpedal or reposition. Then she has to resort to dagger use. \nshe will normally aim at the nearest detected enemy in range.\nThe creature file looks as if they were trying to design (or cut and pasted) a level 12/12 &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Fighter / Thief&lt;/a&gt;, but the scripts and class assignment are fighter only.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod assigns a new default Fighter AI script for potion use, and smarter ranged and melee combat targeting. Weapon proficiencies are redesignated to 5 pips in shortbow and 3 in dagger. This will result in better APR, &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt;, and damage. The arrows of fire are now replaced by &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20of%20Ice\"&gt;Arrow of Ice&lt;/a&gt;.\nSeveral potions are available for scripted use during the battle - for ability boosting/protection and one for healing."}
{"id": "19835", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=19835", "title": "Archer (creature)", "text": "Archers are unique creatures that only appear during the encounter with &lt;a href=\"Senjak\"&gt;Senjak&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dorotea\"&gt;Dorotea&lt;/a&gt;. Their drop loot quite distinct from that of, for example, bandits, and the dialog identifies them as \"Archer\" when they die during a scripted scene."}
{"id": "54827", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=54827", "title": "Archer (illithid hideout)", "text": "Archer is a male elf fighter found in the &lt;a href=\"Illithid%20Hideout%20in%20the%20Sewers\"&gt;Illithid Hideout in the Sewers&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nThere are two of these archers encountered in the second chamber of the illithid complex. \nThe fighters are ostensibly represented as being dire charmed and controlled by the mind flayers and forced to defend against the party's intrusion. This is conveyed by certain on-screen dialogue messages displayed when the encounter occurs.\nThe archers use the WTARSGT script which is focused on ranged combat behavior. As the elves are only armed with bow and arrow, they attempt to stay away from attackers in melee combat and fire from a distance.\nNote that computer-controlled enemies and NPCs don't have to adhere to the same requirements as a player character - as evidenced by their 9 strength and use of a Composite Longbow.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises this fighter. New weapon proficiencies are assigned. Five pips in Long Bow, and three pips in long sword, which is also furnished for melee combat.\nA revised default AI script is assigned for better tactical behavior and potion use.\nThree potions are scripted for use to heal or boost abilities.\nA random scroll is present instead of just random treasure."}
{"id": "29437", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29437", "title": "Archers", "text": ""}
{"id": "40665", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=40665", "title": "Archivist Giltham", "text": "Archivist Giltham, also labelled on the game screen as just \"Archivist\" is an NPC found within &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Altar%20Level\"&gt;Watcher's Keep Altar Level&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nFirst contact with this ghostly creature may be at the very start of exploring the dungeon. This is where the figure will simply remark that it is \"Cold, so very cold...\"\nLater, the Archivist can be activated in the kitchen if the &lt;a href=\"Flint%20and%20Tinder\"&gt;Flint and Tinder&lt;/a&gt; are used on the Fireplace. Starting the roaring fire will draw the spirit to the warmth and seem to generate a spark of \"life\" back to the wandering ghost. He seems unaware of his status of actually being a spirit.\nEngage in dialogue with the creature to gain insight into this dungeon's history and ask some questions if desired.\nNote that the spirit figure is an actor for the plot and roleplaying, not some monster to be killed. It is essentially invulnerable to all attacks. Even if somehow destroyed, it will achieve nothing productive, and no hidden benefit to the player. So don't waste your time and resources flailing away at this non-enemy."}
{"id": "7815", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7815", "title": "Ardenor Crush", "text": "Ardenor Crush is a unique &lt;a href=\"hobgoblin\"&gt;hobgoblin&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\". He is the leader of the &lt;a href=\"Chill\"&gt;Chill&lt;/a&gt;, one of two groups of mercenary bandits hired by &lt;a href=\"Tazok\"&gt;Tazok&lt;/a&gt;, the other being the &lt;a href=\"Blacktalons\"&gt;Blacktalons&lt;/a&gt;, to harass caravans along the Coast Way road between the city of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Nashkel\"&gt;Nashkel&lt;/a&gt;.\nHe is found on the western side of the &lt;a href=\"Bandit%20Camp\"&gt;Bandit Camp&lt;/a&gt; among his fellow &lt;a href=\"Chill%20Hobgoblin\"&gt;Chill Hobgoblin&lt;/a&gt;s, and is immediately distinguishable in a grey tunic.\nHe's not exactly enthusiastic about the alliance between the Chill and the Blacktalons and if &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; insults him, he and four nearby hobgoblins (three Chill hobgoblins and the hobgoblin in front of the &lt;a href=\"Bandit%20Camp%20Cave\"&gt;cave&lt;/a&gt;) will attack. The entire camp turns hostile at this point, but those &lt;a href=\"bandit\"&gt;bandit&lt;/a&gt;s and hobgoblins inside of the tents do not join the fight (although &lt;a href=\"Tersus\"&gt;Tersus&lt;/a&gt; will turn hostile while &lt;a href=\"Knott\"&gt;Knott&lt;/a&gt; won't)."}
{"id": "8568", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8568", "title": "Ardic Santele", "text": " \nArdic Santele lived in &lt;a href=\"Saradush\"&gt;Saradush&lt;/a&gt; was the son of &lt;a href=\"Mirnielle%20Santele\"&gt;Mirnielle Santele&lt;/a&gt;. You will need to find him in connection with the &lt;a href=\"Betrayal%20at%20the%20Gates\"&gt;Betrayal at the Gates&lt;/a&gt; quest. \nIn , you will find him imprisoned in the home of &lt;a href=\"Kiser%20Jhaeri\"&gt;Kiser Jhaeri&lt;/a&gt;. You need to kill Kiser in order to save him."}
